    <section class="content-body">
      <h2>What Is the Pomodoro Technique?</h2>
      <p>The Pomodoro Technique is a time management method created by Francesco Cirillo in the late 1980s. The concept is simple: use a timer to break your work into focused intervals — traditionally 25 minutes — separated by short breaks. Each interval is called a <em>pomodoro</em>, the Italian word for tomato, named after the tomato-shaped kitchen timer Cirillo used as a university student.</p>

      <p>The complete cycle works like this: work for 25 minutes, take a 5-minute short break, then repeat. After four pomodoros, you take a longer break of 15 to 30 minutes. This rhythm of concentrated effort and scheduled rest is what makes the technique so effective.</p>

      <h2>Why the Pomodoro Technique Works</h2>
      <p>The method is effective because it directly addresses the two biggest enemies of productivity: <strong>procrastination</strong> and <strong>burnout</strong>.</p>

      <div class="callout">
        <strong>The Psychology Behind the Timer</strong>
        <p>Committing to "just 25 minutes" of work is psychologically far easier than facing an open-ended task. The fixed time boundary creates urgency that naturally sharpens focus, while the guaranteed break removes the anxiety of working without an endpoint.</p>
      </div>

      <p><strong>It fights procrastination</strong> by reducing the perceived size of any task. Instead of telling yourself you need to work for three hours on a report, you commit to one 25-minute pomodoro. Starting feels effortless. Once you begin, momentum takes over.</p>

      <p><strong>It prevents burnout</strong> by enforcing rest. Most people skip breaks when they are "in the zone," only to crash an hour later with diminished focus. Scheduled breaks keep your mind fresh across the entire workday.</p>

      <p><strong>It builds time awareness.</strong> After a few weeks of using a pomodoro timer, you develop an intuitive sense of how long tasks actually take. This transforms your ability to plan and estimate work — a skill that benefits students, freelancers, and teams alike.</p>

      <h2>How to Use This Pomodoro Timer</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Choose your task</strong> — decide what you will work on before you start the timer.</li>
        <li><strong>Press Start</strong> — the timer begins a 25-minute work session by default.</li>
        <li><strong>Work with full focus</strong> — avoid all distractions until the timer rings. If an interruption comes, note it down and return to your task.</li>
        <li><strong>Take your break</strong> — when the alarm sounds, stop working. The timer automatically switches to a 5-minute break.</li>
        <li><strong>Repeat</strong> — after four pomodoros, a longer 15-minute break begins automatically.</li>
        <li><strong>Customize</strong> — adjust work and break durations to match your rhythm using the settings panel.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Tips for Getting the Most Out of Pomodoro Sessions</h2>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Before You Start</h3>
        <p>Write down 2-3 specific tasks you want to accomplish. Vague goals like "work on the project" lead to unfocused sessions. Specific goals like "write the introduction section" or "fix the login bug" give your pomodoro a clear purpose.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>During Work Sessions</h3>
        <p>Close unnecessary browser tabs, silence your phone, and tell colleagues you are in a focus session. If a thought or task pops into your head, jot it on a piece of paper and return to your work. Do not switch tasks mid-pomodoro.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>During Breaks</h3>
        <p>Step away from your screen. Stretch, get water, look out a window. Avoid checking email or social media — these activities are cognitively demanding and will not recharge you. The goal is to let your mind genuinely rest.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Who Uses the Pomodoro Technique?</h2>
      <p>The method is popular across a wide range of fields. Software developers use it to maintain focus during deep coding sessions. Writers use it to overcome blank-page anxiety. Students use it to study more efficiently for exams. Freelancers use it to structure their workdays without a manager providing external accountability.</p>

      <p>The technique scales to teams as well. Some engineering teams run synchronized pomodoro sessions, where the whole group focuses together and takes breaks together. This reduces the interruptions that fragment individual focus time.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What is the Pomodoro Technique?</summary>
        <p>The Pomodoro Technique is a time management method developed by Francesco Cirillo in the late 1980s. It uses a timer to break work into focused intervals, traditionally 25 minutes long, separated by short breaks. Each interval is called a "pomodoro," the Italian word for tomato, named after the tomato-shaped kitchen timer Cirillo used as a university student.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How long is a standard Pomodoro session?</summary>
        <p>A standard Pomodoro session is 25 minutes of focused work, followed by a 5-minute short break. After completing four pomodoros, you take a longer break of 15 to 30 minutes. These intervals can be adjusted to fit your personal workflow and attention span.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Why does the Pomodoro Technique use 25-minute intervals?</summary>
        <p>Research suggests that 25 minutes is long enough to make meaningful progress on a task but short enough to maintain intense focus without mental fatigue. The fixed time constraint also creates a sense of urgency that helps combat procrastination. However, many practitioners adjust this interval — some prefer 50-minute work sessions with 10-minute breaks.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What should I do during Pomodoro breaks?</summary>
        <p>During short breaks (5 minutes), step away from your work. Stretch, get water, rest your eyes, or do light movement. Avoid checking email or social media as these can pull your focus. During long breaks (15-30 minutes), you can take a walk, have a snack, meditate, or do any non-work activity that helps you recharge mentally.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Can I pause a Pomodoro session?</summary>
        <p>Traditional Pomodoro rules say a pomodoro is indivisible — if you are interrupted, you must either end the pomodoro and start over, or postpone the interruption. In practice, many people do pause when necessary. This timer supports pausing, but for the best results, try to protect your pomodoros from interruptions.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Does the Pomodoro Technique actually improve productivity?</summary>
        <p>Multiple studies have shown that time-boxed work intervals improve focus and reduce mental fatigue. The technique works because it combats two major productivity killers: procrastination (by making tasks feel manageable in 25-minute chunks) and burnout (by enforcing regular breaks). It also builds self-awareness about how long tasks actually take.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What is a tomato timer?</summary>
        <p>A tomato timer is another name for a Pomodoro timer. "Pomodoro" means "tomato" in Italian. The technique was named after the tomato-shaped kitchen timer that inventor Francesco Cirillo used. Today, digital tomato timers replicate the same concept — timing focused work sessions with breaks — without needing a physical kitchen timer.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

    <section class="related-timers">
      <h2>Related Timers</h2>
      <div class="related-grid">
        <a href="/1-minute-timer" class="related-link">1 Minute Timer</a>
